Applying the formula for the stress–energy tensor to the Lagrangian density (the quantity inside the integral), we can derive the stress–energy tensor of the scalar field. It is

:formula_80

and in natural units,

:formula_81

By integration of the time–time component over all space, one may show that both the positive- and negative-frequency plane-wave solutions can be physically associated with particles with &quot;positive&quot; energy. This is not the case for the Dirac equation and its energy–momentum tensor.

The stress energy tensor is the set of conserved currents corresponding to the invariance of the Klein–Gordon equation under space-time translations formula_82. Therefore, each component is conserved, that is, formula_83 (this holds only on-shell, that is, when the Klein–Gordon equations are satisfied). It follows that the integral of formula_84 over space is a conserved quantity for each formula_85. These have the physical interpretation of total energy for formula_86 and total momentum for formula_87 with formula_88.

