This is a &quot;classical&quot; Schrödinger field.

===Quantum field===
The analogous limit of a quantum Klein–Gordon field is complicated by the non-commutativity of the field operator. In the limit , the creation and annihilation operators decouple and behave as independent quantum Schrödinger fields.

==Scalar electrodynamics==

There is a way to make the complex Klein–Gordon field formula_55 interact with electromagnetism in a gauge-invariant way. We can replace the (partial) derivative with the gauge-covariant derivative. Under a local formula_56 gauge transformation, the fields transform as
:formula_102
:formula_103
where formula_104 is a function of spacetime, thus making it a local transformation, as opposed to a constant over all of spacetime, which would be a global formula_56 transformation. A subtle point is that global transformations can arise as local ones, when the function formula_106 is taken to be a constant function.

A well-formulated theory should be invariant under such transformations. Precisely, this means that the equations of motion and action (see below) are invariant. To achieve this, ordinary derivatives formula_107 must be replaced by gauge-covariant derivatives formula_108, defined as 
:formula_109
:formula_110
where the 4-potential or gauge field formula_111 transforms under a gauge transformation formula_112 as 
:formula_113. 
With these definitions, the covariant derivative transforms as
:formula_114 
In natural units, the Klein–Gordon equation therefore becomes
: formula_115

Since an &quot;ungauged&quot; formula_56 symmetry is only present in complex Klein–Gordon theory, this coupling and promotion to a &quot;gauged&quot; formula_56 symmetry is compatible only with complex Klein–Gordon theory and not real Klein–Gordon theory.

In natural units and mostly minus signature we have
where formula_118 is known as the Maxwell tensor, field strength or curvature depending on viewpoint.

This theory is often known as scalar quantum electrodynamics or scalar QED, although all aspects we&#x27;ve discussed here are classical.

=== Scalar chromodynamics ===
It is possible to extend this to a non-abelian gauge theory with a gauge group formula_119, where we couple the scalar Klein–Gordon action to a Yang–Mills Lagrangian. Here, the field is actually vector-valued, but is still described as a scalar field: the scalar describes its transformation under space-time transformations, but not its transformation under the action of the gauge group.

For concreteness we fix formula_119 to be formula_121, the special unitary group for some formula_122. Under a gauge transformation formula_123, which can be described as a function formula_124 the scalar field formula_55 transforms as a formula_126 vector
